# Angular-EasyModal-alert-confirm

This easyModal can be used in AngularJS-base(with Bootstrap) web application, which is an alternative of JS alert and 
confirm dialog with enhanced functionality(html template,css,callback,external controller), more flexible, better user experience.

##Dependencies
Requires AngularJS v1.4.0+ and Bootstrap's CSS.

### Alert Example
```
emodal.alert("<strong>Title</strong> <p></p>Disappear in 2 seconds",2000);
```
### Confirm Example
```
emodal.confirm("Are you sure to delete?",
               function(){
                   //do something if OK is pressed
               },
               function(){
                   //do something if Cancel is pressed
               }
           );
```           

### Modal Example      
```
var okCallbackFun = function (arg) {
            $scope.data = '[ok callback] Parameter: '+arg.id;
        };
var cancelCallbackFun = function (arg) {
            $scope.data = '[cancel callback] Parameter: '+arg.info;
        };
$scope.showModal = function(){
            emodal.modal({
                template:'Messages go here!',
                title:'Callback Function',
                okCallback:okCallbackFun,
                okArgs:{id:1},
                cancelCallback:cancelCallbackFun,
                cancelArgs:{info:'some msg'}
            });
        };     
```        
           
## [Live Usage Examples](http://jsfiddle.net/ttf177/2y7q9nnm/17/) 

## Usage
<h3>1. alert</h3>
 This aims to provide the function like native JS alert, but with more customized properties.  
 There are maximum 3 arguments with four calling types:  
 emodal.alert(string);  
 emodal.alert(string, string);  
 emodal.alert(string, number);  
 emodal.alert(string, string, number);  
<h4>1.1 one argument</h4>    
```
emodal.alert("Messages go here!");
```
<img src="http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-siPJHDXpt3E/Vn1GFPE44xI/AAAAAAAAABY/9Ny6P9Dy0H0/s1600/simple%2Balert.png"/>

<h4>1.2 two arguments</h4>    
//string+string  
```
emodal.alert("Messages go here!","New Button Label");
```
<img src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-Tc571pwKIn8/Vn1GLxpdz0I/AAAAAAAAABg/K3WA0v19iTU/s1600/new%2Bbutton%2Blabel.png">  
OR  
//string+number(millionseconds)   
```
emodal.alert("<strong>Title</strong> <p></p>Disappear in 2 seconds",2000);
```
<img src="http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-MY_3mFjJ-IU/Vn1GMBS2iZI/AAAAAAAAABk/jaVZ1on3rpM/s1600/set%2Bfade%2Btime.png">

1.3 three arguments  
 //message + new label name + millionseconds that the modal vanish  
```
emodal.alert("<strong>Title</strong><p></p>Disappear in 2 seconds","New Button Label",2000);
```
<img src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-P2aEdt-ZGeg/Vn1HW34fXmI/AAAAAAAAAB0/Xy1RYpMffXI/s1600/new%2Bbutton%2Blabel%2Band%2Bfade%2Btime.png">   
<h3>2. confirm</h3>  
 This aims to provide the function like traditional JS confirm, but with more customized properties.  
 There are totally 5 arguments with generally two calling types:  
```
 emodal.confirm(string /*required*/, function /*required*/, function /*optional*/);  
```
 OR  
```
 emodal.confirm(string /*required*/, function /*required*/, function /*optional*/, object /*optional*/, object /*optional*/);  
```
<h4>2.1 three (2 required + 1 optional) arguments</h4>  
 string: message shown in the modal  
 function: callback function if click OK  
 function:(optional) callback function if click Cancel  
```
emodal.confirm("Are you sure to delete?<p></p>It is not recoverable!",
    function(){
        // if OK is clicked
    },
    function(){
         // if Cancel is clicked
     }

);
```
<img src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-mr7e7srjZSk/Vn1JvFhT5cI/AAAAAAAAACA/jEfCUhHnjMM/s1600/simple%2Bconfirm.png">
<h4> 2.2 five (2 required + 3 optional) arguments</h4>  
 string: message shown in the modal  
 function: callback function if press OK  
 function:(optional) callback function if press Cancel  
 object:(optional) "this" object inside okCallback function  
 object:(optional) "this" object inside cancelCallback function  
<h3>3. modal</h3>  
Modal aims to provide more functionality not as simple alert and confirm dialog.  
Generally the argument passed in is an object with the following arguments:  
<img src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-2mmpnDi7yHE/VoVZYHVH-MI/AAAAAAAAAC4/xnYu7Melb_g/s1600/para.png">   
example:
```
emodal.modal("../partials/externalTemplate.html",{title:'External Template'});
```
<img src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-DRfWXspnTec/Vn4lsVqgYHI/AAAAAAAAACc/Mh8mHJMgt2w/s400/msg%2Bfrom%2Bexternal%2Btemplate.png">
